AGI - The Poas> volcano, one of Costa Rica's tourist attractions, has remained in orange alert Monday because of the increase in gases coming out of its crater, which implies greater eruptive potential. The 2,708 meters high colossus, surrounded by a dense forest and 50 km from San José, recorded an intense activity on 1 March, pushing the authorities to limit, but not to suspend, the visits. "We have a lot of information that tells us that there is an influx of fluids from the depths of the region. We do not know what will happen, but it is a contribution that is creating a worrying situation", said to AFP the French volcanologist Geoffroy Avard> of the Volcanological and Symological Observatory of Costa Rica (OVSICORI). "At this time, Poas> is at level three, orange alert, which we call attention. It is level three out of four, and this is because the volcano has many aspects that concern us a lot," he added.
<h2> Volcanic activity in rica</h2>
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
According to the National Seismic Network, Costa Rica is a country with over 120 volcanic outbreaks, but most are extinct and only five remain active: Poas>, Rincon de la Vieja, Arenal, Irazú and Turrialba>. "The volcano is currently very unstable and the form of gas indicates that it is magma", added Ovsicori expert. Visits to the volcano were suspended from April 2017 to August 2018 due to eruptions. They are filmed with enhanced security measures, including shelters and visitor protection devices. "The most significant explosion we have had in the last decade or so was the 2017 eruption, especially the 22 April eruption. The rocks flew for a mile and a half", recalled the volcanologist.
<h2> Impact on local tourism
The suspension of visits has had a strong economic impact on communities living near the volcano, whose income depends on tourism. "The gas prices are increasing a lot," said Cristiano de Freitas, a Brazilian football professor, who said he had the "privilege" to visit Poas>.
&nbsp;

