AGI - The three occupants of the two planes collided were found alive and conscientious after the flight between two Alpha Jet> of the Patrouille de France> (the French acrobatic patrol) in eastern France, which did not cause side casualties, according to the authorities. Created in 1953, the Patrouille de France>, a prestigious air acrobatic training famous especially for its demonstrations during the parades of July 14 in Paris, is composed of carefully selected fighter pilots.
<h2> The dynamics of the accident
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
According to the military air force and space forces, the two planes "apparently clashed" at 15:35 near an air base. According to the Air Force, the pilots and a passenger managed to eject and were "too conscious". "They are in relative emergency conditions", two were transported to the hospital and the third, "multitraumatized, is treated by the army". "There are no side victims," said the prefecture.&nbsp;
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
"Two Alpha Jets of seven members of the Patrouille de France> met during a manoeuvre," said the mayor of Saint-Dizier, Quentin Briere>. One of the planes crashed into a silo and the other "in a swampy and woody area right behind", added the mayor. Tens of firefighters were on the spot in the middle of the afternoon, many of which were spraying water on a still smoking silo on a site owned by the concrete company Calin, near the airbase. Many soldiers, including gendarmes and cops, continued to arrive at the scene.
<h2> accidents
In this elite unit accidents are rare. In 2019, a plane of the Patrouille de France> went out of track in Perpignan (southwest) after a training session, but his pilot managed to eject without problems. In 2002, a pilot of the Patrouille de France> who had activated the ejectable seat died because his parachute did not open completely. In August 2024, two pilots of the Rafale Conversion Squadron of the Saint-Dizier Air Base died in a collision between their planes in Lorraine. Two days later, a period plane crashed into the sea during an air show off Le Lavandou (south), causing the pilot's death.
